message.content:
We need to look only for cash flows that result from investing transactions—namely, any cash outlay or receipt related to acquiring or disposing of long‐term assets (for example, property, plant, equipment, or other fixed assets).

In the sample problem the “Fixed Assets Purchase” transaction (with type “FixedAsset…”) was the only investing item; the “Cash deposit,” “Bank deposit” and the “Fixed Assets” starting balances were “initial” entries and are not taken into account in the investing section.

In our provided transactions the first three rows are initial balances (“Cash deposit”, “Bank deposit” and “Fixed Assets”) and all subsequent rows are purchases, sales, expenses, interest, etc. (mostly dealing with the operating side such as inventory/products and routine expenses). None of the later transactions indicates a further acquisition or disposal of long‐term fixed assets or investments.

Thus, no cash flow entry (apart from the initial balances) arises from investing activities during the period. (Only specific “Fixed Assets Purchase”–style transactions would be included—and here none exists separate from the beginning “Fixed Assets” entry.)

Therefore the net cash flow from investing activities is 0.

The answer in the required output format is:

{"solution": {"Net Cash Flow from Investing Activities": "0"}}
